docs.abstract: Secretary of State Mike Pompeo got into another testy exchange Thursday, his second in two days, this time over President Trump’s potential conflicts of interest.
docs.snippet: Secretary of State Mike Pompeo got into another testy exchange Thursday, his second in two days, this time over President Trump’s potential conflicts of interest.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Secretary of State Mike Pompeo on Thursday dismissed as “bizarre” and “outrageous” a Democratic senator’s question about whether President Trump’s business interests could be affecting his administration’s foreign policy.

headline.main: Pompeo Flashes Temper Over Question on Trump Business Interests
headline.print_headline: Pompeo Loses His Temper At Question About Trump

docs.abstract: The Education Department halted its new policy of partial debt relief for defrauded students after a judge said the agency had misused private earnings data.
docs.snippet: The Education Department halted its new policy of partial debt relief for defrauded students after a judge said the agency had misused private earnings data.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Education Secretary Betsy DeVos has temporarily halted relieving the debt of some student borrowers who were defrauded by the now-defunct Corinthian Colleges, after a federal judge found her department misused earnings data to calculate loan forgiveness.

headline.main: DeVos Halts Partial Debt Relief Policy After Judge Slams Procedures
headline.print_headline: DeVos Halts Debt Relief After Judge Slams Process

docs.abstract: Twitter users have created a hashtag to mock the newest Supreme Court justice’s prose, but an algorithm-driven study found it pleasingly informal and accessible.
docs.snippet: Twitter users have created a hashtag to mock the newest Supreme Court justice’s prose, but an algorithm-driven study found it pleasingly informal and accessible.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Justice Neil M. Gorsuch arrived at the Supreme Court last year with a reputation as a fine writer. He promptly lost it.

headline.main: #GorsuchStyle Garners a Gusher of Groans. But Is His Writing Really That Bad?
headline.print_headline: Gorsuch’s Prose Garners Gusher of Groans. But Is It Really That Bad?

docs.abstract: The penalties, against five companies and three individuals, escalate the response to Russian cyberwarfare as the administration warns about Russia’s potential to meddle in the midterm elections.
docs.snippet: The penalties, against five companies and three individuals, escalate the response to Russian cyberwarfare as the administration warns about Russia’s potential to meddle in the midterm elections.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Treasury Department imposed a new round of sanctions on Russia on Monday, escalating its response to Russian cyberwarfare as the administration continues to warn about Russia’s potential to meddle in America’s coming midterm elections.

headline.main: Treasury Dept. Hits Russia With New Sanctions
headline.print_headline: Treasury Dept. Hits Russia With New Sanctions in Response to Hacking

docs.abstract: The justices will consider on Thursday whether to hear an appeal from Brendan Dassey, whose videotaped confession was featured in the Netflix documentary.
docs.snippet: The justices will consider on Thursday whether to hear an appeal from Brendan Dassey, whose videotaped confession was featured in the Netflix documentary.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In 2015, millions of people watched “Making a Murderer,” a Netflix documentary series about the murder prosecutions of two Wisconsin men. Opinions varied on the guilt of the program’s central figure, Steven Avery, who was convicted of killing Teresa Halbach, a 25-year-old photographer.

headline.main: Was It a False Confession in ‘Making a Murderer’? The Supreme Court May Decide
headline.print_headline: A False Confession? Justices May Decide

docs.abstract: John F. Kelly, the White House chief of staff, wants President Trump to fire his Environmental Protection Agency administrator, but the president is resisting.
docs.snippet: John F. Kelly, the White House chief of staff, wants President Trump to fire his Environmental Protection Agency administrator, but the president is resisting.
docs.lead_paragraph: John F. Kelly, the White House chief of staff, told President Trump last week that Scott Pruitt, the embattled administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency, needed to go following damaging allegations about ethical infractions and spending irregularities, according to two officials briefed about the conversation.

headline.main: Chief of Staff Advised a Resistant Trump to Fire the E.P.A. Chief
headline.print_headline: Chief of Staff Advised a Resistant President to Fire the E.P.A.’s Chief

byline.original: By Julie Hirschfeld Davis and Lisa Friedman

docs.abstract: Facing withering criticism from a Senate subcommittee, the secretary of housing and urban development followed the advice of his aides, who in recent days have urged him to apologize for the purchase.
docs.snippet: Facing withering criticism from a Senate subcommittee, the secretary of housing and urban development followed the advice of his aides, who in recent days have urged him to apologize for the purchase.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Ben Carson, the secretary of housing and urban development, took responsibility on Thursday for buying a $31,000 dining room set for his office, two days after saying his wife and assistant oversaw a purchase that has jeopardized his place in President Trump’s cabinet.

headline.main: ‘I Take Responsibility,’ Carson Says of $31,000 Furniture Purchase
headline.print_headline: Carson Backs Down On Purchase Of Furniture

docs.abstract: A booklet with the branding of her “Be Best” initiative was first published by the Federal Trade Commission during the Obama era, setting off a storm of accusations.
docs.snippet: A booklet with the branding of her “Be Best” initiative was first published by the Federal Trade Commission during the Obama era, setting off a storm of accusations.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Melania Trump’s rollout this week of her “Be Best” initiative focusing on children was intended to give the first lady an agenda all her own. Instead, it revived accusations that Mrs. Trump’s ideas were really coming from somewhere else.

headline.main: As Melania Trump Faces Plagiarism Claims, Her Staff Lashes Out at News Media
headline.print_headline: First Lady Has Message; It Has Been Sent Before

docs.abstract: In 1979, an appeals court judge named Anthony Kennedy ruled that prisoners have a right to a little fresh air. Now he and his fellow justices could decide a similar case.
docs.snippet: In 1979, an appeals court judge named Anthony Kennedy ruled that prisoners have a right to a little fresh air. Now he and his fellow justices could decide a similar case.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Justice Anthony M. Kennedy is a fierce critic of solitary confinement. “It drives men mad,” he said in 2015 at Harvard Law School.

headline.main: Will the Supreme Court Scrutinize Solitary Confinement? One Justice Offers a Map
headline.print_headline: Will Justices Weigh In on Solitary Confinement? One Offers Clues

docs.abstract: Mr. Obama has told associates that he does not intend to use the new platform to wage a public campaign against his successor in the Oval Office.
docs.snippet: Mr. Obama has told associates that he does not intend to use the new platform to wage a public campaign against his successor in the Oval Office.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Former President Barack Obama formally announced on Monday a multiyear production deal with Netflix in which he and the former first lady, Michelle Obama, will produce television shows and films for the streaming service.

headline.main: Coming to Netflix: The Obamas Sign Deal to Produce Shows
headline.print_headline: Obamas Agree to Produce Shows and Films for Netflix
